## Quiz

?? At steady state the capacitor acts like what kind of circuit element?
>> An open circuit. With no changing voltage, $I = C\,dV/dt = 0$. No current flows, no voltage is dropped across R, and all 9 V appear across the capacitor.

?? If we replaced the capacitor with an inductor of the same reactance, what would the roles of the two elements be during the transient?
>> Reversed. At $t = 0$ the inductor opposes any sudden change in current (acting briefly like an *open* circuit — $V_L = L\,dI/dt$ is large), so the initial current is near zero. Over time, current builds up and the inductor settles to a short (no voltage drop). The time constant is $\tau = L/R$ instead of $RC$.
